    {
      "id": "817d3931ed771669e8a0f7932b9b2b2699a38dc9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2021-02-11 17:52:55.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nLinking a userland library to a kernel module is a hard sell. I don't know how are security team would feel about this.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "b7ae462a43c04c382599dbea8752a2ad8a03a7f6",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2021-02-14 23:40:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nlib/raid6.c in Linux should have all the code you need for this - with optimizations for common hardware.\nThere is even an interface to access offload hardware if present.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "c216c7f56b0aad46a4c429a6642f16ad8787e96a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2021-02-15 00:38:15.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> lib/raid6.c in Linux should have all the code you need for this -\n > with optimizations for common hardware.\n > There is even an interface to access offload hardware if present.\n\nDoes that have support for arbitrary M+N erasure coding, or just M+2?  From my quick look at that code it appears hard-coded to be RAID6 (as one would expect from the name) and uses \"disks - 2\".",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "a93a27995e324fd9b96561782938fcedcb313fca",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2021-02-15 02:11:52.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> Does that have support for arbitrary M+N erasure coding\n\nI had a vague memory that it had, but closer inspected suggests not.  There is lib/reed_solomon ... but it works on bytes or words, not blocks.  That's a shame.\n\nIf we do add a dependency to an external library, that'll put another barrier in the way of upstreaming.  It would be nice to do it \"right\" up front, which would mean extending lib/raid6 to handle M+N.  I'm not exactly volunteering, but I might have a look.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "262aff0cf610813055aaf67f7c32a644111778ef",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2021-02-16 16:43:46.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nI talked to Andreas on the slack channel about this and well as having internal discussions. Due to time constraints instead of importing the entire ISA library we are going to take what is needed and place it in libcfs for now.\n\nAs for a long term solution we have pulled in some people that have written erasure codes in the past and discussed what is needed. Yes ORNL is willing to create a general solution to push upstream to Linus tree.\nWe did look at enhancing raid6 but a general solution would be a massive under taking so a separate solution is really needed. It would also be win to look at other implementation besides reed solomon (like weaver).\nTo have this accepted we do need have one user of this work in Linus tree. Currently neither Lustre or bcachefs are merged upstream. Maybe the dm layer?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "310bd009b1d976d94c6d6d0d09c735c5cd4a9dd5",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 805,
        "name": "Neil Brown",
        "email": "neil@brown.name",
        "username": "neilbrown"
      },
      "date": "2021-02-17 23:47:58.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n> To have this accepted we do need have one user of this work in Linus tree. Currently neither Lustre or bcachefs are merged upstream. Maybe the dm layer?\n\nI don't think there is any need to push this work upstream before lustre lands.  It only needs to be designed and implemented so that it would be a good fit for upstream.  Then it can easily be part of the initial submission.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "387579678c163aa8e8a3af4d71aa23a4f7d3b886",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2021-05-04 15:12:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
